doc.ContractDescription: STELLAR, GAS, AND DUST EMISSION OF STAR FORMING GALAXIES OUT TO Z - 2 DUST HAS A PROFOUND IMPACT ON THE FORMATION OF STARS, THE CHEMISTRY OF INTERSTELLAR GAS, AND THE SHAPE OF A GALAXY'S SPECTRAL ENERGY DISTRIBUTION. TRACKING THE COMPLEX INTERPLAY BETWEEN THE STELLAR RADIATION FIELD, GAS-PHASE METALLICITY, AND DUST OVER COSMIC TIME ILLUMINATES THE PROCESSES BY WHICH SMALL-SCALE PHYSICS MANIFESTS INTO LARGE-SCALE PROPERTIES. WE HAVE BEEN USING HUBBLE SPACE TELESCOPE GRISM SPECTROSCOPY AND A WEALTH OF HST AND GROUND-BASED OPTICAL/NEAR-IR PHOTOMETRY IN THE GOODS FIELDS TO MEASURE THE PHYSICAL PROPERTIES AND CHEMISTRY OF ~400 NORMAL STAR-FORMING GALAXIES SPANNING A VERY WIDE RANGE IN STELLAR MASS (7.5<LOG M/ MSUN<10.5), STAR-FORMATION RATE (1<SFR<300 MSUN/YR) AND GAS-PHASE METALLICITY (7<12 + LOG O/H<9). WE PROPOSE TO EXTEND OUR STUDY OF GALACTIC SPECTRAL ENERGY DISTRIBUTIONS TO UV AND MID-IR WAVELENGTHS BY COMBINING OUR HST AND GROUND-BASED DATA WITH OBSERVATIONS FROM SWIFT/UVOT, GALEX, SPITZER/MIPS, AND HERSCHEL/PACS. BY USING SELF-CONSISTENT AND PHYSICALLY MOTIVATED MODELS OF STELLAR POPULATIONS, DUST ATTENUATION, PAH EMISSION, AND DUST EMISSIVITY, AND WE WILL DEFINE THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN GALACTIC DUST ATTENUATION, DUST EMISSION, GAS-PHASE METALLICITY, STELLAR MASS, AND STAR-FORMATION RATE DURING AN EPOCH WHICH IS OFTEN DESCRIBED AS "COSMIC NOON". OUR SPECIFIC GOALS WILL INCLUDE SEARCHING FOR CORRELATIONS BETWEEN DUST ABSORPTION AT 2175 A AND PAH EMISSION, INVESTIGATING THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN GAS-PHASE METALLICITY, DUST MASS, AND PAH STRENGTH, AND EXAMINING HOW THE SYSTEMATIC OF DUST EMISSION VARY ALONG THE FUNDAMENTAL METALLICITY RELATION FROM 1.20<Z<2.35.

ONLY NUSTAR HAS THE SENSITIVITY ABOVE 10 KEV TO DETECT AND ASSESS THE IMPORTANCE OF REFLECTION WHILE INDEPENDENTLY MEASURING THE INTRINSIC SPECTRAL SHAPE IN OUR TARGET SOURCES.
